RDD versus dataframe — when to actually reach for each.

These are two views of the same engine, with very different ergonomics.

The RDD ay-pee-eye is functional and row-by-row. There is no optimizer; your code is the plan. There is no code generation; Python lambdas serialize across to the executors with java virtual machine round-trips. There is no schema. RDDs are slower for structured data, and they are best for unstructured data, custom serialization, and per-partition input output patterns.

The dataframe ay-pee-eye is declarative and column-based. Catalyst rewrites your plan. Tungsten generates java virtual machine bytecode for the hot paths. The schema is required. Dataframes are faster for structured data, and best for almost everything else.

The honest guideline for the rest of this curriculum, and for the bank capstone in the project folder: prefer dataframes. Drop to RDDs only when you need something the dataframe ay-pee-eye genuinely cannot express — a custom map-partitions pattern, a non-tabular input, or a closure that does not fit spark sql.
